{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1937122101/0160.xml":{"full_text":"2\nPresident\u2019s Backing\nSought in Drive for\n\u2018NRA\u2019 in Textiles\nWith Wage Bill Beaten, Bloc May Also Ask\nfor U. S. Rule of Steel, Other Industries\nBy WILLIAM S. NEAL\n(Copyright. 1937, by International News Service)\nProposals for enactment of a \u201clittle NRA\" to rule the huge\ntextile industry sprang up today in the wake of the defeat of\ngeneral minimum wage and maximum hours legislation in the\nPilots\u2019 Head\nUrges\u2018Safe\u2019\nField Here\nHj\u00df?* a\nDAVID L. BEHNCKE\nCongress today was urged to\nenact legislation at the next ses\nsion to provide Washington with\na safe airport.\nIn a letter to every member of\nCongress, David L. Behncke, presi\ndent of the Airline Pilots Associa\ntion, urged speedy action be taken\nto eliminate the Washington air\nport which he termed \u2018'danger\nous.\u2019\u2019\nSAFETY MEASURE\nBehncke also urged that Con\ngress place safety control of air\ncommerce in the hands of the In\nterstate Commerce Commission.\nPointing out that in the last two\nyears there have been 16 major\nair line accidents, with 115 fatali\nties, Behncke declared the main\nstumblingblock in the success of\nair transportation is the problem\nof safety.\nRAILWAYS CITED\nHe urged that the ICC be dele\ngated to handle this rather than\nthe Department of Commerce,\nwhich he described as primarily a\ntrade-promoting agency.\nUnder the ICC the railways of\nthe country have reached a high\ndegree of safety, he pointed out,\nand believes that similarly the air\nlines would be made safer under\nthe commission regulation.\nColorado Picket\nTaboo Is Removed\nDENVER, Dec. 21 (1.N.5.).\nStrikers today held the right to\npicket in Colorado for the first\ntime since 1905.\nDistrict Judge Henry A. Hicks,\nMonday, declared the Stated 32-j\nyear-old anti picketing statute un\nconstitutional. The ruling was!\nhanded down in a test case,\nbrought to determine validity of!\nthe law.\nNEW CLUBHOUSE\nThe Palm Beach (fla.) Yacht\nClub is building a new clubhouse\nand hopes to have the structure\nin time for the annual Washing\nton\u2019s Birthday regatta on Lake\nWorth next February.\njSEfeIMES\npublished Daily at 1317 H fit. N W\nwith Sunday Issue as the Washington i\nHerald-Times\nEditorial and Business Phone\nRepublic 1234\nPntered ex :A* Poss O//tcs. Wa* Ampron\nD. C., \u00aba tecond-clcM mail malitr.\nEleanor PatUrroc Editor and Publish*!\nWiUUw G Shelton Aaaociat* Publiah*!\nRATES BT CARRIER IN WASHINGTON DC\nAND SUBURBS\nDally and\nDally Sunday Sunday\nOna Tear *5.20 *5 10 *lO 40\nSix Months 2 60 2.60 5.20\nThraa Month* 1 SO 1.30 1.66\nOn* Month 4* .4* -\u00bb0\nOe* Wash .1*.1420\nBATES BT MAIL TOR VIRGINIA. MARTLAND.\nWEST VIRGINIA AND NORTH CAROLINA\nDaily and\nDally Sunday Bunday\nOn* Tear *6 04 *6.00 *12.00\n\u2022is Watha 50 3.50 t oo\nThree Month* 1.&0 l.so *.so\nOn* Meath .4060 1.20\nOTHER STATES. CANADA AND MEXICO\nDaily ano\nDaily Bunday Bunday j\nOne Tear *7.*o 1f.20 115.n0\nSix Months S M f 50\nThree Month* 1.45 *-75\nOn* Maith .65 .60 1.25\nALt MAIL Btr\u00df?rirpTTON\u00df PAYABLE\nIN ADVANCE\nTefapAoM* RE public 1234\nHouse.\nA drive also may be launched\nto bring the steel industry, and\n'perhaps one or two other big in\ndustries. under government rule\nI\njon the pattern of the national\nbituminous coal act.\nSEEK ROOSEVELT AID\nWhile President Roosevelt has\ninformed congressional leaders\n[that an effort should be made in\nthe regular session to work out a\nnew wage-hour bill, sponsors of\nthe \u201clittle NRA\u2019\u2019 plan will appeal\nto him to also sanction their\nmovement.\nThe Ellenbogen textile bill, which\nreceived Administration support\nbefore it was decided to frame a\nnational minimum wage and maxi\nmum hours bill, will be consid\nered by the House Labor Com\nmittee in January.\nLeaders in the movement as\nserted that a textile bill could be!\npushed through Congress in a'\ncomparatively short time, if given 1\nWhite House sanction, while it\nwould take months to get a new\nI general wage-hour bill in shape.\nPRESIDENT DISAPPOINTED\nPresident Roosevelt was re\nported to have been keenly dis\nappointed by action of the House\nin recommitting the wage-hoyr\nbill to the labor committee for!\nfurther study.\nFirmly convinced that the prin-|\nciple of the legislation must be\nenacted, he has informed con\ngressional leaders that Senate\nand House labor committees\nshould begin consideration of\nsuch legislation in the regular\nsession.\nConferences were planned by\nsome congressional leaders on a\nproposed plan to enact a national\n40-hottr veik, providing for ex\nceptions for seasonal industries,\n(and omit all reference to wages.\nThe proposal is expected to be\ni laid before Mr. Roosevelt in the\nnear future for his approval.\nStabilization Pool\nTo Be Advocated\nLONDON, Dec. 21 (I.N.S.)\u2014In\na report to be given the British\nand French governments before\nChristmas, according to the Eve\nning News today, Paul Van Zee\nland, former premier of Belgium\nand outstanding financial au\nthority, will recommend pooling of\nAmerican, British and French\nforeign exchange equalization\nifunds. Van Zeeland will urge the\nj step as an aid to more stable cur\nrency conditions, said the News.\nFirestone Raps\nU. S. Regulation\nMIAMI BEACH. Fla., Dec. 21\n(I.N.S.).\u2014Harvey S. Firestone,\nrubber magnate, attributes the\n(business recession to government\n'regulation of industry, and says:\n\u201cIf we want to regain our\nI prosperity we must do an about\nI face on regulation. In other\nwords our prosperity still\ndepends on two fundamentals\n\u2014work and production.\u201d\nTwin Girls Upset\nColes\u2019 Name Plans\nHOLLYWOOD. Dec. 21 (1.N.5.).|\nRussel Coles, jr., film actor, and\nhis wife, Dorothy, know just what 1\ntheir son's name was going to be.\nBut today they hunted for a set\nof girls\u2019 names, for Mrs. Coles pre\nsented her husband with twin\ndaughters.\nToday In\nCongress\nSENATE\nMeets at noon.\nBegins consideration of housing\nbill.\nHOUSE\nMeets at noon.\nHears speeches, marking time\nj until adjournment.\nl Ways and Means Subcommittee\ncontinues tax revision study.\nIncome Taxes Advance\nOne-Half in Year\n(1.N.5.) A healthy rise in income tax receipts was\nreflected in Treasury figures today, as revenues for the\nfiscal year passed the $3,000,000,000 mark.\nIncome taxes since July 1 have produced $1,079,000,000,\nnearly 50 per cent more than a year ago.\nIncome levies for the first 18 days of this month pro\nduced $408,253,195, compared with 238.852,507 collected\nduring the corresponding period of 1936.\nRevenues since July 1 amounted to $3,019,879,380, as\nagainst $2,042,194,354 in the same period a year earlier.\nHousing Boom Bill\nSpeeded in Senate\nBy ARTHUR HACHTEN\n(1.N.5.) Racing down the homestretch toward adjournment\nof the special session of Congress, the Senate today began con\nsideration of the Wagner-Steagall housing-boom bill.\n\u201cWe are going to try to pass\nthe bill and send it to President\nRoosevelt for signature by\nThursday and then adjourn the\nspecial session of the Christmas-\nNew Year holidays,\u201d said Senate\nMajority Leader Barkley.\n\u201cThe housing bill is all we ex\npect to get through between now\nand adjournment,\u201d he added in\nexpressing personnel preferences\nto be \u201chome in Kentucky for\nChristmas.\u201d\nASKS ACTION NOW\nPresident Roosevelt, in a special\nmessage to Congress November 27,\nasked that a measure to stimulate\nhome construction be passed\n\u201cnow,\u201d to help stem the business\nrecession. Apparently, it will be\nthe only major recovery measure\nfinally passed by the extraordinary\nsession of Congress.\nHowever, Administration\nleaders felt much had been\naccomplished in getting the farm\naid bills of the Senate and House\nto conference during the brief\nspecial session. Had the farm\nissue been held up until the re\ngular session, beginning January\n3, it might have taken several\nmonths to put it on the statute\nbooks, they said.\nRecommittal of the wage-hour\nbill by the House was a major\nblow to the Administration.\nUP TO HOUSE\n\u201cThat problem is still on the\ndoor-step of the House,\u201d said\nBarkljy.\nUnless a torrent of debate on\nthe housing bill Is unloosed in\nthe Senate, adjournment of Con\ngress Wednesday was considered\nprobable. No difficulties in ad\njusting differences between the\nSenate and House bills was ex\npected and advocates of the\nmeasure were looking for a Christ\nmas spirit to prevail\u2014Senators\nwilling to compromise.\nWhile the bill, as passed by the\n39 ARMY MEN\nARE PROMOTED\nPromotion of 39 officers in the\nRegular Army to higher rank was't\nannounced by the War Department t\ntoday. f\nThe promotions, which take es- j\nfeet immediately, affect all\nbranches of the service and in-\nelude: f\nJudge Advocate General\u2019s De\npartment, Col. Allen M. Burdett.\nQuartermaster Corps, Majors\nWillis A. Platts, Rene E. de Russy\nand Edward M. George. t\nCorps of Engineers, Major Clay\nAnderson. i\nOrdnance Department, Col, Wai- i\nter P. Boatwright.\nCavalry, Lieut. Cols. James N. i\nCaperton and Harrison Herman t\nand Major Samuel R. Goodwin. 1\nField Artillery, Col. Marshall i\nMagruder, Lieut. Col. Douglas J. i\nPage and Major Irvin B. Warner.\nCoast Artillery Corps, Cols. John\nP. Smith and Edwin K. Smith,\nI Lieut. Cols. Frank C. Scofield, Fer\ndinand F. Gallagher and Barring\nton L. Flanfgen and Major George\nW. Ames.\nInfantry, Cols. George R. Koeh\nler and Oliver S. Wood; General\nStaff Corps, Lieut. Cols. George\nJ. Newgarden, jr., John F. Good\nman and Robert K. Whitson, and\nMajors Vernon C. de Votie, Clyde\nGrady, Horace J. Brooks, Morgan\nE. Jones, George H. Rarey and\nJacob E. Uhrig.\nAir Corps, Col. Robert E. M.\nGoolrick and Major Arthur W.\nBrock, jr.\nMedical Corps, Lieut. Cols. Lu\ncius K. Patterson, Charles R. Muel\nler, Charles F. Davis and Clarence\nIM. Reddig and Capts. John T. B.\n(strode and Paul H. Leach.\nDental Corps, Lieut Col. Daniel\n|S. Lockwood.\nVeterinary Corps, Capt. Velmer\nI W. McGinnis.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, TUESDAY, DECEMBER 21, 1937\n(House, would revive Government\nmortgage insurance for home re\npairs and remodeling, the Senate\nmeasure does not contain that\nfeature. Restriction were carried\nin the Senate bill\u2019against Govern\nment-owned or Government con\ntrolled home mortgage agencies\ncompeting with private capital in\nsingle-family dwellings. The Gov\nernment would be required to con\nfine its direct operations to large\nscale projects.\nMAJOR DIFFERENCES\nWhile the House bill would au\nthorize national mortgage associa\ntions to issue debentures up to 20\ntimes their paid-in capital, the\nSenate bill would cut that to 15\ntimes.\nj Another major difference be\ntween the Senate and House meas\nures was a limitation of 3,000 mil\nlion dollars in the Senate bill on\nthe face amount of mortgages that\ncould be insured by the Govern\nment, whereas the House bill fixes\na top of 2,000 million dollars, with\ndiscretionary authority for the\nPresident to add 1,000 million dol\nlars.\ni Both bills were alike in authoriz\ning the Federal Housing Admin\nistration to insure up to $5,400 on\nhomes valued at $6,000 and 80\nper cent on loans between $6,000\nand SIO,OOO. Above SIO,OOO, the\n80 per cent limitation would pre\nvail.\n1942 TIME LIMIT\nThis more liberal mortgage\ninsurance policy would continue\nuntil 1942 under the Senate bill,\nbut there is no time limit in the\nHouse bill. As a further induce\nment to small-home builders, the\nSenate bill would permit 25-year\namortization on small-loan homes\napproved before July 1,1939. After\nthat date a 20-year maximum\nwould prevail.\nTREASURY GETS\nMELLON CANVAS\nRepresentatives of the estate of\nthe late Andrew W. Mellon, whose\nmodesty would not permit him to\nfurnish a portrait for exhibition\nin the Treasury \"Hall of Fame\u201d\nduring his lifetime, have an\nnounced that they will furnish a\nportrait to be placed in the Treas\nury.\nThe portrait will occupy the\nconspicuous place in the office of\nSecretary of the Treasury Morgen\nthau now occupied by a portrait\nof Senator William G. McAdoo,\nwho was Secretary of the Treasury\nunder Woodrow Wilson.\nSecretary Morgenthau said that\nit has been customary for por\ntraits of former secretaries to ro\ntate through the halls, the most\nrecent one each time being placed\nin the reception room.\nBritish Refugees\nFace Closed River\nSHANGHAI, Dec. 21 (1.N.5.).\nThirty British women and chil\ndren aboard the British patrol\nboat Cape Town today faced\nthe prospect of being trapped in\nthe Yangtze River.\nPostal and Western Union\nTo Ask 15 Pct. Rate Rise\nAnnouncement was made today\nthat the telegraph companies are\npreparing to apply to the Federal\nCommunications Commission for a\n15 per cent increase in rates.\nThe companies will contend that\nthe \u201cfinancial resources and credit\nof the companies are being jeopar\ndized by the decline in revenue\nBULK OF EXCISE\nTAXES RETAINED\nUNDER NEW PLAN\n\u201cHot Oil\u201d Among Those\nTo Be Repealed\n(1.N.5.) The House Ways and\nMeans tax subcommittee has de\ncided to recommend repeal of ex\ncise and nuisance taxes yielding\n$25,000,000 a year, it was disclosed\nofficially today.\nThe plan calls for dropping of\nnine levies on which the yield is\ncomparatively small and cost of\ncollection is high. All of them\noriginated in the billion-dollar\n\u201cbudget balancing\u201d bill of 1932,\nand have been continued from\ntime to time.\nLEVIES DROPPED\nLevies to be dropped include\nthose on sales of sporting goods,\nsoap, tooth paste, brewers\u2019 malt,\nchewing gum, cameras, phono\ngraph records, furs and the one\neighth of a cent a barrel tax levied\nto pay cost of administration of\nthe \u201chot oil\u201d act.\nAt the same time an increase in\ntaxes on paper book matches \u2014at\nthe request of manufacturers\u2014\nwas revealed.\nMATCH TAX EVENED\nThis novel situation grew out\nof the difference between taxes\non different classes of matches.\nThe tax on ordinary box matches\nis two cents per 1,000, while the\ntax on paper book matches is one\nhalf cent per thousand. The sub\ncommittee decided to retain the\nbox match tax and raise the tax\non paper book matches to two\ncents.\nThe decision to drop excise, or\nmanufacturers* sales, taxes yield\ning $25,000,000 a year inferentlally\ncarries with it decision to retain\nthe bulk of this class of tax\nlevies, yielding a total of $650,-\n000,000 a year.\nRETAINS GAS TAX\nAmong the levies which the sub\ncommittee has not disturbed are\nthe Federal gasoline tax, yielding\n$190,000,000 a year; taxes on new\nautomobiles, trucks, accessories,\ntires, tubes, lubricating oil, me\nchanical refrigerators, yachts, 3-\ncent postage, transfer taxes, levies\non theater admissions, telegraph\nand telephone messages, cosmet\nics, radios, and the import taxes\non oil, copper, lumber and coal.\nAll of these levies were re\nenacted in the last session of Con\ngress for a two-year period.\nTwo Lawyers Face\n\u2018Unethical\u2019 Probe\nTwo attorneys and two bonds\nmen, cited by a grievance com\nmittee of the District Bar Associa\ntion last week for alleged uneth\nical practices, were to appear in\nPolice Court at 11 a. m. today,\nto show cause why they should\nnot be prosecuted.\nThe lawyers, William P. Mullen\nand Henry D. Green, and Bonds\nmen Hyman Mendelson and Jo\nseph P. McGee were to appear\nbefore the four judges of the Po\nlice Court sitting en banc. Charges\nagainst the four will oe presented\nby Austin Canfield, chairman of\nthe bar association\u2019s grievance\ncommittee, and several other\nmembers of the bar association.\nJersey Shelves\nHousing Program\nTRENTON. N. J., Dec. 31\n(I.NS.). \u2014State housing aid was\nshelved in New Jersey today. The\nlegislature adjourned sine die last\nnight after refusing to act upon\nhills to enable municipalities to\nobtain Federal funds for low-cost\nhousing and slum-clearance proj\nects, despite warning that failure\nto pass the bills might result in\nloss of $35,000,000 to $30,000,000\n\u2022in Federal aid.\nbrought on by the general slacken\ning of the business of the country,\non which the industry depends.\u2019*\nThe situation, the companies\ncontend, is made critical by the\ngrowing cost of telegraph opera\ntion through heavy social security\nand other taxes, wages, mainten\nance and mounting expenses of all\nkinds.\nSenate Peace Block\nDemands Neutrality\nAct Strengthening\nPanay Incident Whets Drive for Bill to Be\nPut Through Next Session\nBy ROBERT A. McGILL\n(1.N.5.) Alarmed over the war in the Far East, the Senate\npeace bloc demanded speedy enactment of legislation at the\nnext session of Congress.\nThe drive for legislative guar\nantees that the United States re\nmain free of all foreign entangle\nments gained momentum as ten\nsion over the Japanese bombing\nof the gunboat Panay, and other\nacts of violence involving the\nUnited Stats, swept the Senate.\nLAFOLLETTE BACKS PLAN\nMembers of the Senate Muni\ntions Committee announced they\nwill demand immediate considera\ntion of their program to strengthen\nthe Neutrality act, while individual\ngroups clamored for recognition\nof their legislative barriers against\nthe United States participating in\na foreign war.\nSenator LaFollette (P.) of Wis\nconsin, said he expects to call up\nhis peace program early in the\nsession.\nIt provides for an amendment\nto the constitution which would\nprohibit the President to declare\nwar on a foreign nation unless\nratified by a majority of votes\ncast in a nation-wide referendum.\nIt also prohibits the Congress\nfrom conscripting men for mili\ntary service overseas unless such\nan act be confirmed by popular\nreferendum.\nCAPPER OFFERS PROGRAM\nA similar resolution in the\nHouse, sponsored by Represen\ntative Ludlow (D.) of Indiana,\nhas already brought sharp criti\ncism from President Roosevelt\nand the State Department.\nSenator Capper (R.) of Kansas,\nis sponsoring a six-point program\nto keep the United States out of\na foreign war. It also calls for a\nCHILD LABOR\nDOOM DRGED\n(1.N8.) Demands for imme\ndiate legislation, to stamp out child\nlabor were made in the Senate\nyesterday by Senator Vanderberg\n(R.) of Michigan.\nAlthough the House sent the\nwage-hour bill back to committee\nlast Friday the child labor issue,\nupon which there is general agree\nment, should not be allowed to\ndie, he said.\nTO RECEIVE PARENTS\nA general reception for parents\nwill be given by teachers of the\nBancroft School at 8 o\u2019clock to\nnight. The reception will be held\nin the school\u2019s classrooms.\neh,w h\nNo wonder it's eopopdot\u2019. Pay wooWy yTHTJOI\nor twice o month \u2014that\u2019s afif\nNo extra charge for this sewien. v\n1535FSt.N.W. (J 7 t\nSTORE HOURS 9 A.M. TO 6 P.M.\n7**Z\u00abpAon\u00ab REpublie 1234\nSEN. LA TOLLETTE\nconstitutional amendment \u201cgiving\nthe people the right to vote on\nforeign wars,\u201d and demands that\nthe United States \u201ckeep out of\nthe League of Nations and all\nalliances with other nations that\nwould mean policing the world.\u201d\nA resolution that would ban\nfurther trade agreements with na\ntions \u201csituated either in the Eu\nropean or Asiatic war zone,\u201d is\nsponsoied by Senator Lodge (R.)\nof Massachusetts.\nSeveral bills designed to \u201ctake\nthe profits out of war,\u201d and permit\nthe Government to confiscate im\nportant war industries in time of\nemergency are before various Sen\nate committees.\nN.Y. GAB STRIKE\nGOES TO PARLEY\nNEW YORK, Dec. 21 (1.N.5.).\nMoving \u201cto avoid bloodshed,\u201d\nMayor LaGuardia today halted for\nthe time being the spreading\nstrike of taxicab drivers by call\ning a peace conference between\noperators and union represent\natives.\nThe mayor named Nathan Fran\nkel, director of the Industrial Re\nlations Board, to sit as negotiator\nafter Otto G. Gutfreund, general\nmanager of Sunshine Radio Sys\ntem cabs, had telegraphed his\nfears of violence should the strike,\nwhich already has tied up 1,600\nof the city\u2019s 13,000 cabs, continue\nto spread.\nU. S. FAR DEHIND\nFOREIGN POWERS\nIN CARGO BOATS\nBlds Are Asked on 12\nFast Vessels\nBy THEODORE HUNTLEY\nBack of President Rosevelt\u2019s de\ntermination to strengthen the\nNavy, expected to express itself in\na request sos larger naval appro\npriations when Congress meets in\nJanuary, lies some significant fig\nures.\nThey show the United States\nNavy to be numerically strong and\npotentially stronger still in rela\ntion to the navies of other world\npowers. But they also show it to\nbe short of modern warships and,\nas authorities agree, dangerously\ndeficient in a merchant marine\ncapable of conversion in emergency\nto naval uses.\n12 BOATS ORDERED\nComparative studies, for ex\nample, disclose the United States\nto be outranked in merchant ves\nsels, so necessary in time of war,\nby England, Germany, Japan,\nFrance and Italy. In modem ships\nit has fallen far behind.\nThe Maritime Commission has\njust asked for bids fox the con\nstruction of 12 fast cargo boats\nwhich could be quickly converted\ninto naval auxiliaries and an\nnounced that in considering the\nproposals preference will be given\nbidders who can make the fastest\ndeliveries. This is a recognition\nof our weakness in auxiliary ship\nping.\nU. S. RANKS SEVENTH\nHers are the actual figures on\nthe number and total tonnage of\nmerchant ships constructed by the\nsix principal powers in the last\nten years:\nNo. Ships Tom\nGreat Britain 704 4,407,000\nGermany 112 >47.000\nJapan 11l 704,000\nFranca 54 500.000\nItaly 43 433,000\nUnited States 41 417.000\nAll this means that America\u2019s\nocean-going ships are smaller and\nslowet than those of other na\ntiona, This fact, added to the cix\ncunjstance that England am\nJapan both possess several time\nas many merchant ships as th\nUnited States, emphasizes the!\nhandicap under which the United\nStates would labor if trouble\nbroke, since these vessels would\nbe needed to carry commerce, war\nsupplies and possibly troops.\nN. Y. Armored Car\nPlays Santa Role\nNEW YORK, Dec. 21.\u2014An ar\nmored car drew up at the Clinton\nStreet police station and uniformed\nguards, with pistols in their belts,\nproceeded to unload armfuls of\ndolls, drums, balls, skates, minia\nture trains and automobiles and\nother toys.","height":"26040","width":"20524"}}
